293
00:10:20,760 --> 00:10:21,280
of course,

294
00:10:21,300 --> 00:10:23,040
one way of getting the a priori probability

295
00:10:23,040 --> 00:10:25,060
would just be to flip it a zillion times,

296
00:10:25,300 --> 00:10:27,680
and after a zillion flips,

297
00:10:27,980 --> 00:10:30,920
you could count how many of each kind you got.

298
00:10:31,540 --> 00:10:33,140
But that's not what we're going to do.

299
00:10:33,180 --> 00:10:34,110
We're not going to try to

300
00:10:34,110 --> 00:10:35,040
study this air in this room

301
00:10:35,040 --> 00:10:37,320
by doing a zillion replicas of the room.

302
00:10:37,440 --> 00:10:37,600
I mean,

303
00:10:37,600 --> 00:10:38,520
we will do that mathematically,

304
00:10:39,160 --> 00:10:40,140
but not physically.

305
00:10:41,220 --> 00:10:42,580
And so,

306
00:10:42,740 --> 00:10:44,280
someplace else,

307
00:10:44,340 --> 00:10:46,440
we have to get the basic ideas

308
00:10:46,440 --> 00:10:48,100
of a priori probability

309
00:10:48,660 --> 00:10:49,280
from.

310
00:10:53,720 --> 00:10:56,320
You might go back a step

311
00:10:56,320 --> 00:10:57,000
and say,

312
00:10:57,000 --> 00:10:58,020
if the dye

313
00:10:58,660 --> 00:11:01,180
is not really a fair dye,

314
00:11:03,020 --> 00:11:05,940
then the probability is going to depend,

315
00:11:06,080 --> 00:11:06,980
or may depend,

316
00:11:07,140 --> 00:11:08,820
on all kinds of things.

317
00:11:08,820 --> 00:11:11,380
It may depend on details,

318
00:11:11,760 --> 00:11:14,540
such as the way the hand flips it,

319
00:11:14,640 --> 00:11:16,700
the air currents in the room,

320
00:11:16,960 --> 00:11:18,540
the nature of the surface,

321
00:11:18,700 --> 00:11:20,500
that it may or may not bounce off,

322
00:11:20,700 --> 00:11:22,640
all kinds of details

323
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:25,120
which are extraneous to the system itself.

324
00:11:25,600 --> 00:11:26,500
In other words,

325
00:11:26,520 --> 00:11:27,900
it may depend on the environment

326
00:11:27,900 --> 00:11:29,160
as well as the system.

327
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:31,100
So,

328
00:11:31,100 --> 00:11:33,220
the idea of an a priori probability

329
00:11:33,540 --> 00:11:34,200
for the dye

330
00:11:34,820 --> 00:11:37,200
may not be such a good idea after all.

331
00:11:40,660 --> 00:11:42,900
You have mentioned the fact that you have

332
00:11:42,900 --> 00:11:45,240
implicitly assumed a time symmetry

333
00:11:45,240 --> 00:11:46,960
in which you can...

334
00:11:47,740 --> 00:11:50,160
We are going to implicitly assume

335
00:11:50,160 --> 00:11:51,100
time symmetry,

336
00:11:51,300 --> 00:11:51,940
and in fact,

337
00:11:51,940 --> 00:11:53,640
we're going to talk about that

338
00:11:53,640 --> 00:11:54,840
sort of right now.

339
00:11:57,060 --> 00:12:00,260
Let's add a dynamical element

340
00:12:00,260 --> 00:12:01,720
to the idea,

341
00:12:01,920 --> 00:12:04,820
which may help us get a handle

342
00:12:04,820 --> 00:12:07,540
on this idea of a priori probability.

343
00:12:10,040 --> 00:12:11,680
The cube here,

344
00:12:11,840 --> 00:12:12,360
the dye,

345
00:12:12,640 --> 00:12:14,780
let's think of it as a dynamical system.

346
00:12:15,180 --> 00:12:17,300
A dynamical system means

347
00:12:17,300 --> 00:12:19,620
one which changes with time

348
00:12:19,620 --> 00:12:22,020
under some law of motion.

349
00:12:22,580 --> 00:12:24,160
A law of motion

350
00:12:24,160 --> 00:12:26,680
is simply an updating process.

351
00:12:27,260 --> 00:12:28,460
It tells you if you

352
00:12:28,460 --> 00:12:29,660
know the state of the system

353
00:12:29,660 --> 00:12:30,800
at one instant of time,

354
00:12:31,020 --> 00:12:32,940
it tells you what the instant...

355
00:12:32,940 --> 00:12:33,720
what the state will be

356
00:12:33,720 --> 00:12:35,140
in the next instant of time.

357
00:12:35,460 --> 00:12:37,520
That's the idea of a law of motion.

358
00:12:37,540 --> 00:12:40,600
An updating from one instant to the next.

359
00:12:40,760 --> 00:12:41,340
Now,

360
00:12:41,340 --> 00:12:42,120
of course,

361
00:12:42,140 --> 00:12:43,600
with the motion of particles

362
00:12:43,600 --> 00:12:44,620
and things like that,

363
00:12:44,700 --> 00:12:45,840
the motion is nice and smooth

364
00:12:45,840 --> 00:12:46,440
and continuous,

365
00:12:46,800 --> 00:12:48,700
and you can subdivide the time

366
00:12:48,700 --> 00:12:51,540
into infinitesimal elements.

367
00:12:51,940 --> 00:12:53,580
But if we're talking about a dye,

368
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:56,460
the closest thing we could imagine to that

369
00:12:56,460 --> 00:12:59,940
is that the dye executes operations

370
00:13:01,020 --> 00:13:02,220
one per...

371
00:13:02,220 --> 00:13:02,840
Now,

372
00:13:02,840 --> 00:13:03,620
per what?

373
00:13:04,180 --> 00:13:07,520
Per elementary time in it.

374
00:13:07,540 --> 00:13:07,760
Per interval.

375
00:13:07,980 --> 00:13:08,900
In other words,

376
00:13:08,900 --> 00:13:10,420
we imagine dividing up time

377
00:13:10,420 --> 00:13:11,760
into equal segments.

378
00:13:12,040 --> 00:13:13,420
We will not take the limit.

379
00:13:13,940 --> 00:13:15,220
And at each instant,

380
00:13:16,540 --> 00:13:18,980
the dye rearranges itself

381
00:13:20,540 --> 00:13:22,580
in a way that only depends

382
00:13:22,580 --> 00:13:25,160
on what's showing at the top of the dye.

383
00:13:26,400 --> 00:13:26,920
Okay,

384
00:13:26,920 --> 00:13:28,580
so we could represent that law

385
00:13:28,580 --> 00:13:29,960
and in this...

386
00:13:29,960 --> 00:13:31,820
in previous versions of this class,

387
00:13:31,980 --> 00:13:33,420
we have talked about this kind of thing

388
00:13:33,420 --> 00:13:34,480
several times,

389
00:13:35,140 --> 00:13:36,520
but you can represent

390
00:13:36,520 --> 00:13:38,380
the motion of the dye

391
00:13:38,380 --> 00:13:40,340
as a rule.

392
00:13:41,080 --> 00:13:41,560
Okay,

393
00:13:41,560 --> 00:13:42,040
so let's see.

394
00:13:42,100 --> 00:13:43,780
I have some rules written down here.

395
00:13:44,520 --> 00:13:45,780
Let me give you some rules.

396
00:13:46,280 --> 00:13:47,360
Here's the first one.

397
00:13:50,079 --> 00:13:52,540
If the top of the dye is red,

398
00:13:53,439 --> 00:13:55,480
then in the next instant...

399
00:13:55,480 --> 00:13:55,980
Let's see,

400
00:13:55,980 --> 00:13:56,520
where is it?

401
00:14:00,860 --> 00:14:01,340
Yeah.

402
00:14:01,960 --> 00:14:03,220
Red goes to blue.

403
00:14:04,920 --> 00:14:05,960
If it's blue,

404
00:14:05,960 --> 00:14:09,120
blue goes to yellow.

405
00:14:10,100 --> 00:14:11,160
If it's yellow,

406
00:14:11,860 --> 00:14:13,360
yellow goes to green.

407
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:15,040
If it's green,

408
00:14:15,900 --> 00:14:17,060
green goes to orange.

409
00:14:17,720 --> 00:14:19,020
And if it's orange,

410
00:14:20,600 --> 00:14:22,120
orange goes to purple.

411
00:14:22,640 --> 00:14:23,820
And if it's purple,

412
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:25,660
purple goes back to red.

413
00:14:27,020 --> 00:14:28,580
We could represent this

414
00:14:28,580 --> 00:14:29,580
as a kind of diagram.

415
00:14:29,920 --> 00:14:34,880
We could put six colors down.

416
00:14:36,880 --> 00:14:37,360
Red,

417
00:14:37,360 --> 00:14:37,840
blue,

418
00:14:37,840 --> 00:14:39,560
yellow,

419
00:14:39,560 --> 00:14:40,980
green,

420
00:14:40,980 --> 00:14:42,660
orange,

421
00:14:42,660 --> 00:14:43,380
purple.

422
00:14:43,600 --> 00:14:44,980
And then just draw some arrows.

423
00:14:45,380 --> 00:14:46,520
Red goes to blue,

424
00:14:46,640 --> 00:14:47,460
blue goes to yellow,

425
00:14:47,600 --> 00:14:48,460
yellow goes to green,

426
00:14:48,620 --> 00:14:49,540
green goes to orange,

427
00:14:49,720 --> 00:14:50,660
orange goes to purple,

428
00:14:50,800 --> 00:14:51,960
purple goes back to red.

429
00:14:52,900 --> 00:14:53,380
Okay?

430
00:14:53,460 --> 00:14:56,060
That would be a complete dynamical theory

431
00:14:56,060 --> 00:14:57,340
of a very,

432
00:14:57,340 --> 00:14:58,720
very simple system,

433
00:14:58,900 --> 00:14:59,840
the dyes,

434
00:14:59,840 --> 00:15:00,240
the dye.

435
00:15:01,820 --> 00:15:02,300
Okay?

436
00:15:02,300 --> 00:15:02,840
Now,

437
00:15:02,840 --> 00:15:05,780
supposing the motions occurred quickly.

438
00:15:06,020 --> 00:15:07,800
Let's suppose they happened fast.

439
00:15:08,240 --> 00:15:09,960
So fast that they happened,

440
00:15:09,960 --> 00:15:10,380
let's say,

441
00:15:10,440 --> 00:15:11,700
in less than a blink of an eye.

442
00:15:12,580 --> 00:15:13,860
And now we ask,

443
00:15:13,980 --> 00:15:16,520
I don't care whether the dye is weighted funny

444
00:15:16,520 --> 00:15:17,880
or not weighted funny.

445
00:15:18,020 --> 00:15:18,720
It doesn't matter.

446
00:15:18,960 --> 00:15:20,200
This is the rules.

447
00:15:20,600 --> 00:15:22,820
This is the rules of motion of the dye.

448
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:25,460
And it spends equal amounts of time

449
00:15:25,460 --> 00:15:29,040
in between each successive motion.

450
00:15:29,960 --> 00:15:31,840
Then it's pretty darn clear

451
00:15:31,840 --> 00:15:34,240
that if I just randomly sample it

452
00:15:34,240 --> 00:15:35,440
at an instant of time,

453
00:15:35,620 --> 00:15:37,980
as it's going from one to the other very fast,

454
00:15:38,320 --> 00:15:40,200
if I randomly sample it,

455
00:15:40,300 --> 00:15:42,580
it's pretty darn clear that I will have

456
00:15:42,580 --> 00:15:46,220
an equal probability of getting any one of the six,

457
00:15:46,420 --> 00:15:46,580
one,

458
00:15:46,580 --> 00:15:46,780
two,

459
00:15:46,780 --> 00:15:47,040
three,

460
00:15:47,040 --> 00:15:47,280
four,

461
00:15:47,280 --> 00:15:47,520
five,

462
00:15:47,560 --> 00:15:47,900
one,

463
00:15:47,900 --> 00:15:48,240
two,

464
00:15:48,240 --> 00:15:48,520
three,

465
00:15:48,520 --> 00:15:48,760
four,

466
00:15:48,760 --> 00:15:49,000
five,

467
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:49,640
six colors.

468
00:15:50,260 --> 00:15:50,740
Right?

469
00:15:50,840 --> 00:15:52,380
Just because they each spend

470
00:15:52,380 --> 00:15:54,780
the same amount of time,

471
00:15:54,920 --> 00:15:55,540
or each,

472
00:15:55,540 --> 00:15:57,900
the dye spends the same amount of time

473
00:15:59,260 --> 00:16:01,300
being in each one of these states.

474
00:16:01,900 --> 00:16:03,160
So it's pretty darn clear,

475
00:16:03,300 --> 00:16:04,440
I don't think I need to prove it,

476
00:16:04,520 --> 00:16:06,300
that this would be a situation

477
00:16:06,760 --> 00:16:07,420
in which

478
00:16:12,620 --> 00:16:14,520
the probability would be one sixth,

479
00:16:14,680 --> 00:16:15,460
as you would expect.

480
00:16:16,120 --> 00:16:17,960
Now this is fairly robust.

481
00:16:18,520 --> 00:16:21,280
We could replace this law by other laws.

482
00:16:21,980 --> 00:16:22,480
Let's see,

483
00:16:22,480 --> 00:16:23,100
I have another one.

484
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:24,620
I think I have two others written down.

485
00:16:31,660 --> 00:16:32,260
Well,

486
00:16:32,260 --> 00:16:35,940
we could just replace blue by green,

487
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:37,220
and green by blue,

488
00:16:37,920 --> 00:16:40,300
and maybe change some other ones.

489
00:16:40,500 --> 00:16:41,640
It wouldn't make any difference.

490
00:16:41,980 --> 00:16:45,660
So there are many possible laws like this,

491
00:16:46,420 --> 00:16:49,760
all of which would lead to the same one sixth.

492
00:16:50,880 --> 00:16:52,960
So it's fairly robust in a sense.

493
00:16:53,180 --> 00:16:54,600
But is it completely robust?

494
00:16:54,620 --> 00:16:55,200
No.

495
00:16:55,700 --> 00:16:57,620
I'll give you an example of a law

496
00:16:58,500 --> 00:16:59,920
which gives a different answer,

497
00:17:00,040 --> 00:17:01,560
or which doesn't give an answer altogether,

498
00:17:01,920 --> 00:17:02,200
really,

499
00:17:02,200 --> 00:17:02,900
that's the point.

500
00:17:03,680 --> 00:17:04,160
Okay,

501
00:17:04,160 --> 00:17:04,880
so here it is.

502
00:17:07,099 --> 00:17:08,540
Red goes to blue.

503
00:17:10,460 --> 00:17:10,940
Blue,

504
00:17:10,940 --> 00:17:11,500
let's see,

505
00:17:11,500 --> 00:17:12,240
what do I have here?

506
00:17:12,800 --> 00:17:13,960
Blue goes to green.

507
00:17:16,700 --> 00:17:19,020
And green goes back to red.

508
00:17:21,079 --> 00:17:22,599
Yellow goes to purple.

509
00:17:23,859 --> 00:17:25,460
Purple goes to,

510
00:17:25,460 --> 00:17:26,260
what have I left out?

511
00:17:26,359 --> 00:17:26,680
Orange.

512
00:17:27,520 --> 00:17:29,700
And orange goes back to yellow.

513
00:17:31,020 --> 00:17:31,680
All right,

514
00:17:31,680 --> 00:17:32,980
now at every stage,

515
00:17:33,200 --> 00:17:35,440
whatever the state of the system is,

516
00:17:35,640 --> 00:17:37,200
it tells you what to do next.

517
00:17:37,360 --> 00:17:38,560
There's nothing wrong with this rule.

518
00:17:38,960 --> 00:17:40,970
It does have a funny property

519
00:17:40,970 --> 00:17:42,980
relative to this one over here.

520
00:17:43,260 --> 00:17:44,740
What is that funny property?

521
00:17:46,160 --> 00:17:46,680
Well,

522
00:17:46,680 --> 00:17:48,740
maybe the easiest way...

523
00:17:48,740 --> 00:17:49,500
It has two orbits.

524
00:17:49,680 --> 00:17:50,680
It has two orbits.

525
00:17:51,560 --> 00:17:53,180
This has one orbit.

526
00:17:53,640 --> 00:17:55,360
This has two orbits.

527
00:17:55,840 --> 00:17:56,960
Or two cycles.

528
00:17:57,720 --> 00:17:58,620
You might say cycles.

529
00:17:58,920 --> 00:17:59,460
In fact,

530
00:17:59,460 --> 00:18:00,320
if you graphed it,

531
00:18:00,480 --> 00:18:01,220
you graphed it,

532
00:18:01,220 --> 00:18:02,000
you might have red,

533
00:18:04,140 --> 00:18:04,740
blue,

534
00:18:04,740 --> 00:18:05,340
green,

535
00:18:07,640 --> 00:18:08,700
back to red,

536
00:18:08,900 --> 00:18:13,020
and yellow to purple,

537
00:18:13,880 --> 00:18:14,960
to orange,

538
00:18:15,820 --> 00:18:16,900
back to yellow.

539
00:18:17,360 --> 00:18:18,860
Two distinct cycles.

540
00:18:19,520 --> 00:18:20,120
Now,

541
00:18:20,120 --> 00:18:20,660
there's no way that you can say,

542
00:18:20,660 --> 00:18:22,160
there's no way a priori

543
00:18:22,720 --> 00:18:25,420
to know what the probability is

544
00:18:25,420 --> 00:18:27,740
that you're on this cycle or that cycle.

545
00:18:28,900 --> 00:18:30,300
If you're on this cycle and

546
00:18:30,300 --> 00:18:31,700
you know you're on this cycle,

547
00:18:31,840 --> 00:18:33,920
and you whip around it real fast,

548
00:18:34,360 --> 00:18:36,520
then obviously the probability is

549
00:18:36,520 --> 00:18:38,540
one-third to be red,

550
00:18:38,540 --> 00:18:38,940
blue,

551
00:18:38,940 --> 00:18:39,380
or green,

552
00:18:40,100 --> 00:18:41,680
and zero to be yellow,

553
00:18:41,680 --> 00:18:42,200
purple,

554
00:18:42,200 --> 00:18:42,840
or orange.

555
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:44,940
But on the other hand,

556
00:18:45,020 --> 00:18:48,140
all you may have is also statistical knowledge,

557
00:18:48,260 --> 00:18:49,020
where it came from,

558
00:18:49,020 --> 00:18:50,060
let's not worry about now,

559
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:52,760
about whether you're on this cycle or this cycle.

560
00:18:53,760 --> 00:18:55,140
And in that case,

561
00:18:55,400 --> 00:18:56,880
it would be more complicated.

562
00:18:57,240 --> 00:18:59,380
I'll leave it to you to calculate if it was,

563
00:18:59,420 --> 00:19:00,060
of course,

564
00:19:00,060 --> 00:19:01,080
if it was a half a half,

565
00:19:01,980 --> 00:19:03,050
probability of a half of

566
00:19:03,050 --> 00:19:04,120
this and a half of that,

567
00:19:04,620 --> 00:19:06,960
then you would reduce yourself back to one-sixth.

568
00:19:07,320 --> 00:19:08,760
But if it was probability

569
00:19:08,760 --> 00:19:10,200
one-third to be on this cycle,

570
00:19:10,320 --> 00:19:12,000
and two-thirds to be on that cycle,

571
00:19:12,100 --> 00:19:13,040
then it would be more complicated.

572
00:19:13,300 --> 00:19:14,480
I'm not going to work it out right now.

573
00:19:15,460 --> 00:19:15,860
Okay,

574
00:19:15,860 --> 00:19:18,020
so this is a counterexample

575
00:19:18,020 --> 00:19:22,200
to the statement that there's equal a priori probabilities

576
00:19:22,200 --> 00:19:23,180
for all configurations.

577
00:19:23,920 --> 00:19:26,120
But this system,

578
00:19:26,260 --> 00:19:28,020
or with this law of nature,

579
00:19:28,300 --> 00:19:29,760
this law of motion,

580
00:19:30,160 --> 00:19:34,680
there is something called a conserved quantity.

581
00:19:36,520 --> 00:19:39,920
Let's define a quantity z.

582
00:19:40,280 --> 00:19:41,860
Z is for zilch.

583
00:19:42,080 --> 00:19:43,240
This is the zilch.

584
00:19:43,680 --> 00:19:47,580
The zilch has a value either one or zero.

585
00:19:48,020 --> 00:19:49,220
It's equal to one

586
00:19:53,320 --> 00:19:54,520
for red,

587
00:19:54,520 --> 00:19:54,940
blue,

588
00:19:54,940 --> 00:19:55,580
or green.

589
