We're talking about quite deterministic rules.

1168
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:05,200
Yes,

1169
00:39:05,200 --> 00:39:05,480
we're talking,

1170
00:39:05,480 --> 00:39:05,780
yes.

1171
00:39:05,880 --> 00:39:06,340
The world,

1172
00:39:06,340 --> 00:39:08,180
at least the classical world,

1173
00:39:08,180 --> 00:39:09,200
is deterministic.

1174
00:39:09,420 --> 00:39:11,320
It's only apparently statistical.

1175
00:39:11,960 --> 00:39:13,460
It's apparently statistical,

1176
00:39:13,460 --> 00:39:15,590
and we're going to talk about

1177
00:39:15,590 --> 00:39:17,720
the conditions why it is apparently statistical.

1178
00:39:18,220 --> 00:39:19,660
But I will tell you right now,

1179
00:39:19,660 --> 00:39:20,760
it's apparently,

1180
00:39:20,760 --> 00:39:22,560
a system is apparently statistical,

1181
00:39:24,280 --> 00:39:25,960
typically because it's coupled.

1182
00:39:26,080 --> 00:39:26,840
It's coupled to a much,

1183
00:39:26,840 --> 00:39:29,700
much bigger system about which you know very little.

1184
00:39:30,420 --> 00:39:31,840
And a heat bath,

1185
00:39:31,840 --> 00:39:32,600
in other words.

1186
00:39:33,340 --> 00:39:37,540
And you don't know enough about the

1187
00:39:37,540 --> 00:39:41,740
heat bath to specify the details of it.

1188
00:39:41,920 --> 00:39:43,140
But that's always the case.

1189
00:39:43,280 --> 00:39:43,500
I mean,

1190
00:39:43,500 --> 00:39:46,740
that things are random.

1191
00:39:46,900 --> 00:39:48,020
Not always the case,

1192
00:39:48,020 --> 00:39:50,120
but it's the case in

1193
00:39:50,120 --> 00:39:52,220
classical physics that things are random,

1194
00:39:52,320 --> 00:39:54,140
not because there's any intrinsic

1195
00:39:54,140 --> 00:39:55,960
randomness in the laws of physics,

1196
00:39:56,080 --> 00:39:58,760
but because you simply don't know enough.

1197
00:39:58,920 --> 00:39:59,880
You don't specify.

1198
00:39:59,980 --> 00:40:01,200
We're going to talk about that.

1199
00:40:01,280 --> 00:40:02,600
That's the basic idea of entropy.

1200
00:40:06,080 --> 00:40:06,860
All right,

1201
00:40:06,860 --> 00:40:07,420
in any case,

1202
00:40:07,420 --> 00:40:10,320
this principle of the conservation

1203
00:40:10,320 --> 00:40:13,220
of distinctions is so important.

1204
00:40:13,340 --> 00:40:16,990
It's rarely mentioned because it is so

1205
00:40:16,990 --> 00:40:20,640
deeply assumed by everybody who does classical physics

1206
00:40:20,640 --> 00:40:23,080
that it is rarely mentioned as

1207
00:40:23,080 --> 00:40:25,520
one of the laws of thermodynamics.

1208
00:40:26,380 --> 00:40:29,210
I would call it the zeroth law of thermodynamics,

1209
00:40:29,740 --> 00:40:31,430
except the zeroth law of thermodynamics

1210
00:40:31,430 --> 00:40:33,120
is also used for something else.

1211
00:40:33,740 --> 00:40:35,630
So we could call it

1212
00:40:35,630 --> 00:40:37,520
the minus first law of thermodynamics.

1213
00:40:38,580 --> 00:40:43,000
And it is the most central fact that must

1214
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:47,420
be true for thermodynamics or statistical mechanics to make sense

1215
00:40:48,080 --> 00:40:52,280
and for it to predict the consequences of thermodynamics,

1216
00:40:52,280 --> 00:40:53,220
the theory of heat.

1217
00:40:54,040 --> 00:40:55,140
So it's a...

1218
00:40:55,140 --> 00:40:56,120
It's,

1219
00:40:56,120 --> 00:40:58,220
as I say,

1220
00:40:58,220 --> 00:41:00,380
built into the structure of classical mechanics.

1221
00:41:00,600 --> 00:41:03,800
What is the relevant statement about classical mechanics?

1222
00:41:06,180 --> 00:41:07,400
Classical mechanics,

1223
00:41:07,400 --> 00:41:07,860
of course,

1224
00:41:07,860 --> 00:41:09,880
does not deal with these very,

1225
00:41:09,880 --> 00:41:10,700
very trivial...

1226
00:41:10,700 --> 00:41:11,960
I use these as illustration,

1227
00:41:11,960 --> 00:41:14,080
illustration of a concept.

1228
00:41:15,100 --> 00:41:16,220
But of course,

1229
00:41:16,220 --> 00:41:18,880
classical mechanics deals with continuous systems,

1230
00:41:18,880 --> 00:41:22,780
systems of coordinates and momenta.

1231
00:41:24,640 --> 00:41:26,340
For our purposes now,

1232
00:41:26,340 --> 00:41:28,900
momentum can just be mass times velocity.

1233
00:41:30,320 --> 00:41:33,510
And each coordinate of a system

1234
00:41:33,510 --> 00:41:36,700
has associated with it a momentum,

1235
00:41:36,840 --> 00:41:40,220
namely its time derivative times the mass of the object.

1236
00:41:40,860 --> 00:41:41,480
And...

1237
00:41:42,160 --> 00:41:43,260
But of course,

1238
00:41:43,260 --> 00:41:44,420
there is a deeper,

1239
00:41:44,420 --> 00:41:47,140
more profound meaning to the idea of a momentum.

1240
00:41:47,360 --> 00:41:49,260
We've talked about it in classical mechanics.

1241
00:41:49,640 --> 00:41:51,120
For the purpose of this class,

1242
00:41:51,120 --> 00:41:52,620
momentum can just mean...

1243
00:41:52,780 --> 00:41:52,980
It's a very,

1244
00:41:52,980 --> 00:41:52,980
very simple definition of momentum.

1245
00:41:52,980 --> 00:41:53,640
And it's a state of momentum with conventional momentum,

1246
00:41:53,640 --> 00:41:57,760
although there may be situations where you want to

1247
00:41:57,760 --> 00:42:01,880
keep track of a more profound definition of momentum.

1248
00:42:02,700 --> 00:42:03,240
All right.

1249
00:42:03,240 --> 00:42:05,040
So what is the state of a system?

1250
00:42:05,040 --> 00:42:07,990
The state of the system for this simple example

1251
00:42:07,990 --> 00:42:10,940
of a single die was just a label color,

1252
00:42:10,940 --> 00:42:12,420
state the color.

1253
00:42:12,920 --> 00:42:15,640
If you know the color,

1254
00:42:15,640 --> 00:42:16,520
you know it comes next

1255
00:42:16,520 --> 00:42:17,400
and you know it comes before.

1256
00:42:17,720 --> 00:42:19,740
If it's a case of two dice,

1257
00:42:19,740 --> 00:42:21,440
then it's a pair.

1258
00:42:21,440 --> 00:42:22,770
The state of the system is

1259
00:42:22,770 --> 00:42:24,100
labeled by a pair of colors.

1260
00:42:24,560 --> 00:42:27,400
What about a single point particle?

1261
00:42:27,400 --> 00:42:31,060
A single point particle is

1262
00:42:31,060 --> 00:42:34,720
labeled by a collection of coordinates,

1263
00:42:34,720 --> 00:42:35,320
x,

1264
00:42:35,320 --> 00:42:35,740
y,

1265
00:42:35,740 --> 00:42:36,180
and z,

1266
00:42:36,180 --> 00:42:37,380
or x1,

1267
00:42:37,380 --> 00:42:37,700
x2,

1268
00:42:37,700 --> 00:42:38,180
x3,

1269
00:42:38,180 --> 00:42:38,540
x,

1270
00:42:38,540 --> 00:42:38,700
y,

1271
00:42:38,700 --> 00:42:39,040
and z.

1272
00:42:39,580 --> 00:42:41,770
That's the coordinates of the

1273
00:42:41,770 --> 00:42:43,960
particle and the corresponding momentum,

1274
00:42:43,960 --> 00:42:44,720
the x,

1275
00:42:44,720 --> 00:42:44,980
y,

1276
00:42:44,980 --> 00:42:46,660
and z components of the momentum.

1277
00:42:47,800 --> 00:42:48,400
Equivalently,

1278
00:42:48,400 --> 00:42:48,840
the x,

1279
00:42:48,840 --> 00:42:49,040
y,

1280
00:42:49,040 --> 00:42:50,560
and z components of the velocity.

1281
00:42:51,400 --> 00:42:54,390
But for reasons that go

1282
00:42:54,390 --> 00:42:57,380
into the depths of classical mechanics,

1283
00:42:58,520 --> 00:43:01,100
the momenta are the right things to describe it by.

1284
00:43:01,540 --> 00:43:03,160
The symbol for momenta,

1285
00:43:03,160 --> 00:43:05,840
the historical symbol for momentum,

1286
00:43:05,840 --> 00:43:07,040
is p,

1287
00:43:07,680 --> 00:43:10,500
and the historical symbol for coordinates is,

1288
00:43:10,500 --> 00:43:10,840
of course,

1289
00:43:10,840 --> 00:43:11,240
x.

1290
00:43:13,860 --> 00:43:18,420
There are three p's and three x's for each particle,

1291
00:43:18,420 --> 00:43:19,790
so I draw it as just

1292
00:43:19,790 --> 00:43:21,160
a p and an x plane.

1293
00:43:21,520 --> 00:43:22,040
But,

1294
00:43:22,040 --> 00:43:22,400
of course,

1295
00:43:22,400 --> 00:43:24,040
for an ordinary particle,

1296
00:43:24,040 --> 00:43:26,400
there would be a three-dimensional p space

1297
00:43:26,400 --> 00:43:27,380
and a three-dimensional x plane.

1298
00:43:27,400 --> 00:43:30,240
So it gets complicated fast.

1299
00:43:30,940 --> 00:43:32,920
The picture of the phase space,

1300
00:43:32,920 --> 00:43:34,300
this is called the phase space,

1301
00:43:34,600 --> 00:43:39,540
the phase space of a classical particle is six-dimensional.

1302
00:43:41,360 --> 00:43:43,160
What is the x space called?

1303
00:43:43,160 --> 00:43:44,120
Just x by itself,

1304
00:43:44,120 --> 00:43:45,280
without worrying about p.

1305
00:43:47,100 --> 00:43:48,860
It's called a configuration space.

1306
00:43:49,280 --> 00:43:53,560
So the configuration space is the space of x's,

1307
00:43:53,560 --> 00:43:57,160
the phase space is the space of x's and p's.

1308
00:43:57,160 --> 00:44:00,470
But what constitutes a state of

1309
00:44:00,470 --> 00:44:03,780
a particle is not an x,

1310
00:44:03,780 --> 00:44:05,060
but an x and a p.

1311
00:44:05,560 --> 00:44:08,190
And the reason is that in order to

1312
00:44:08,190 --> 00:44:10,820
say where a particle is going to be next,

1313
00:44:11,160 --> 00:44:13,280
you not only have to know where it is,

1314
00:44:13,280 --> 00:44:14,700
but you have to know how it's moving.

1315
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:18,900
You have to know both its position and its momentum,

1316
00:44:18,900 --> 00:44:19,920
or the position and velocity.

1317
00:44:20,540 --> 00:44:22,120
So for a single particle,

1318
00:44:22,120 --> 00:44:24,740
the x's and the p's,

1319
00:44:27,160 --> 00:44:31,500
are like the color of the surface of the dice.

1320
00:44:31,680 --> 00:44:34,180
It labels a state of the particle.

1321
00:44:34,460 --> 00:44:36,120
For many particle systems,

1322
00:44:36,120 --> 00:44:41,660
there are many x's and many p's.

1323
00:44:42,140 --> 00:44:43,600
If there are ten particles,

1324
00:44:43,600 --> 00:44:45,120
how many x's are there?

1325
00:44:46,380 --> 00:44:46,940
Thirty.

1326
00:44:47,960 --> 00:44:48,520
x,

1327
00:44:48,520 --> 00:44:48,800
y,

1328
00:44:48,800 --> 00:44:50,320
and z for all ten particles.

1329
00:44:50,820 --> 00:44:51,380
px,

1330
00:44:51,380 --> 00:44:51,560
py,

1331
00:44:51,560 --> 00:44:53,720
and pz for all ten particles.

1332
00:44:54,300 --> 00:44:55,440
So what do we say?

1333
00:44:55,440 --> 00:44:56,860
There were thirty x's,

1334
00:44:56,860 --> 00:44:57,960
thirty p's,

1335
00:44:58,080 --> 00:44:59,100
so for ten particles,

1336
00:44:59,100 --> 00:45:01,500
sixty coordinates to the phase space.

1337
00:45:02,840 --> 00:45:05,180
And so it gets complicated fast.

1338
00:45:05,760 --> 00:45:08,240
For a system of ten to the twenty-third particles,

1339
00:45:08,240 --> 00:45:09,840
I won't try to draw it.

1340
00:45:12,900 --> 00:45:16,240
It's six times ten to the twenty-third dimensional space.

1341
00:45:16,860 --> 00:45:17,520
But now,

1342
00:45:17,520 --> 00:45:20,420
what does it mean to say,

1343
00:45:20,420 --> 00:45:21,520
well first of all,

1344
00:45:21,520 --> 00:45:22,380
what is an orbit?

1345
00:45:22,380 --> 00:45:24,060
What is a history?

1346
00:45:24,700 --> 00:45:26,080
A starting point,

1347
00:45:26,080 --> 00:45:30,120
which could be like the analog of starting with red,

1348
00:45:30,360 --> 00:45:32,860
is just a starting point in this phase space.

1349
00:45:33,440 --> 00:45:36,180
And then the equations of motion,

1350
00:45:37,300 --> 00:45:39,600
either Newton's equations or whatever

1351
00:45:39,600 --> 00:45:41,900
equations are governing the system,

1352
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:44,760
allow you to follow it.

1353
00:45:45,240 --> 00:45:47,180
So you follow it with time.

1354
00:45:47,340 --> 00:45:51,440
These little ticks here could be microseconds.

1355
00:45:52,380 --> 00:45:54,000
But of course the motion is continuous,

1356
00:45:54,000 --> 00:45:55,080
but you could nevertheless,

1357
00:45:55,360 --> 00:45:57,880
you could divide it up into microseconds if you like,

1358
00:46:00,380 --> 00:46:01,640
or what's smaller,

1359
00:46:01,640 --> 00:46:02,600
nanoseconds,

1360
00:46:02,600 --> 00:46:03,600
or whatever you want to do,

1361
00:46:03,700 --> 00:46:05,480
and draw the trajectory.

1362
00:46:05,740 --> 00:46:08,360
And that's the trajectory in the phase space.

1363
00:46:08,600 --> 00:46:10,680
It's not the trajectory of the object in space,

1364
00:46:11,180 --> 00:46:14,520
it's the trajectory through this phase space.

1365
00:46:14,960 --> 00:46:16,180
Wherever you start,

1366
00:46:17,400 --> 00:46:17,880
oh,

1367
00:46:17,880 --> 00:46:19,780
there are various kinds of situations,

1368
00:46:19,780 --> 00:46:22,360
and we can talk about them.

1369
00:46:22,600 --> 00:46:23,740
In some of them,

1370
00:46:23,740 --> 00:46:27,400
the trajectories just wander off and go to infinity.

1371
00:46:27,700 --> 00:46:28,580
For example,

1372
00:46:28,580 --> 00:46:29,960
just for a free particle,

1373
00:46:30,560 --> 00:46:31,480
a free particle,

1374
00:46:31,480 --> 00:46:32,380
if you give it a shove,

1375
00:46:32,380 --> 00:46:33,800
it just goes off to infinity.

1376
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:35,280
Its momentum doesn't change,

1377
00:46:35,280 --> 00:46:37,140
so p is constant,

1378
00:46:37,380 --> 00:46:39,260
but x just goes off to infinity.

1379
00:46:39,640 --> 00:46:42,080
But for the kinds of systems we're interested in,

1380
00:46:42,200 --> 00:46:45,020
the systems which are contained within finite boxes,

1381
00:46:45,660 --> 00:46:46,580
as a rule,

1382
00:46:46,580 --> 00:46:48,740
the system will,

1383
00:46:48,740 --> 00:46:54,620
will not leak off to infinity,

1384
00:46:54,900 --> 00:46:58,240
but it will somehow usually wind up coming back,

1385
00:47:00,500 --> 00:47:03,980
or perhaps not coming back to exactly the same point,

1386
00:47:04,180 --> 00:47:05,180
but it's,

1387
00:47:05,180 --> 00:47:08,700
that's a bad drawing.

1388
00:47:09,240 --> 00:47:10,860
That's not a good drawing,

1389
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:13,380
because it illustrates something exactly

1390
00:47:13,380 --> 00:47:15,760
the thing which doesn't happen.

1391
00:47:16,500 --> 00:47:17,580
It illustrates exactly,

1392
00:47:17,580 --> 00:47:18,660
the problem,

1393
00:47:19,320 --> 00:47:21,080
the problem is two dimensions,

1394
00:47:21,200 --> 00:47:24,560
it's too low a dimension to draw a good picture.

1395
00:47:25,700 --> 00:47:26,300
Okay,

1396
00:47:26,300 --> 00:47:27,460
what doesn't happen,

1397
00:47:27,640 --> 00:47:28,660
what doesn't happen,

1398
00:47:28,740 --> 00:47:32,080
and now this is a theorem of classical mechanics,

1399
00:47:33,140 --> 00:47:35,200
and it has several pieces to it.

1400
00:47:35,460 --> 00:47:40,460
The first statement is that trajectories don't merge.

1401
00:47:41,960 --> 00:47:43,100
Never happens.

1402
00:47:44,359 --> 00:47:44,880
All right?

1403
00:47:44,980 --> 00:47:47,400
This is the analog of saying,

1404
00:47:47,400 --> 00:47:49,960
that distinctions are preserved.

1405
00:47:51,640 --> 00:47:53,280
Distinctions are conserved.

1406
00:47:53,600 --> 00:47:55,920
The two different starting points never

1407
00:47:55,920 --> 00:47:58,240
lead to the same end point.

1408
00:47:58,920 --> 00:47:59,400
Okay?

1409
00:47:59,700 --> 00:48:01,640
And also the opposite is true.

1410
00:48:02,420 --> 00:48:03,080
Of course,

1411
00:48:03,080 --> 00:48:04,420
this wouldn't make any sense at all.

1412
00:48:04,660 --> 00:48:07,000
A given starting point splits in two.

1413
00:48:07,260 --> 00:48:08,320
What on earth would that mean?

1414
00:48:08,400 --> 00:48:10,040
You start at some given starting point,

1415
00:48:10,100 --> 00:48:11,260
and you,

1416
00:48:11,520 --> 00:48:13,520
that would mean it's not deterministic.

1417
00:48:13,700 --> 00:48:15,800
It would mean you don't know where you go next

1418
00:48:15,800 --> 00:48:17,180
when you get to this point over here.

1419
00:48:17,580 --> 00:48:19,000
Those things don't happen.

1420
00:48:19,140 --> 00:48:21,080
Trajectories don't cross.

1421
00:48:21,540 --> 00:48:22,360
Number one,

1422
00:48:22,360 --> 00:48:22,960
they don't cross.

1423
00:48:23,260 --> 00:48:24,140
And number two,

1424
00:48:24,140 --> 00:48:25,520
they don't merge.

1425
00:48:26,080 --> 00:48:28,660
So a trajectory doesn't cross like that.

1426
00:48:29,160 --> 00:48:30,300
They never do that.

1427
00:48:31,280 --> 00:48:32,620
And they never merge.

1428
00:48:39,720 --> 00:48:42,080
Now there can be conserved quantities.

1429
00:48:42,420 --> 00:48:43,240
In other words,

1430
00:48:43,240 --> 00:48:44,880
the trajectories can be labeled,

1431
00:48:45,040 --> 00:48:45,660
for example,

1432
00:48:45,660 --> 00:48:46,760
with values of energy.

1433
00:48:47,400 --> 00:48:49,640
The energy doesn't change along a trajectory.

1434
00:48:50,220 --> 00:48:51,660
It's much like the zilch.

1435
00:48:51,800 --> 00:48:53,240
It doesn't change along the trajectory.

1436
00:48:53,640 --> 00:48:55,940
And so the different trajectories in general,

1437
00:48:56,820 --> 00:48:57,840
whatever they do,

1438
00:48:59,080 --> 00:49:01,200
may be labeled by the energy.

1439
00:49:02,320 --> 00:49:04,100
And that energy doesn't change.

1440
00:49:04,700 --> 00:49:06,560
You pick it once and for all,

1441
00:49:07,380 --> 00:49:08,700
and it stays that way.

1442
00:49:09,860 --> 00:49:10,940
So that's,

1443
00:49:10,940 --> 00:49:11,280
again,

1444
00:49:11,280 --> 00:49:12,140
what is that called?

1445
00:49:12,220 --> 00:49:13,540
